    "subject": "Civil Procedure - Dispositive Motions",
    "rule": "Rule 12 Motion to Dismiss (Timing, Procedures, and Defenses for Failure to State a Claim)",
    "question": "When a defendant files a Rule 12(b)(6) motion to dismiss and supports it with matters outside the pleadings, what automatic conversion rule applies?",
    "trigger": "A defendant files a 12(b)(6) motion and attaches a contract document to show the complaint mischaracterizes its terms. The plaintiff does not object to consideration of the document.",
    "notes": "- If **matters outside the pleadings are presented with a 12(b)(6) motion**, the motion **converts to a summary judgment motion** under Rule 56 (unless the court excludes the extrinsic material)\n- Exception: Documents **integral to and explicitly relied upon in the complaint** may be considered without conversion (the \"incorporation by reference\" doctrine)\n- **Plaintiff must be given notice and opportunity** to respond as if summary judgment motion was filed\n- **Burden shifts**: No longer a facial pleading sufficiency test; court may consider evidence beyond the complaint\n- Court has discretion to **exclude extraneous materials** to preserve 12(b)(6) as a pure pleading motion",
