    "rule": "Effect of Judgment (Elements of Claim Preclusion / Res Judicata & Issue Preclusion)",
    "question": "What is the test for whether two claims arise from the 'same cause of action' under the modern transactional test for claim preclusion?",
    "trigger": "Plaintiff sued for breach of a single construction contract seeking damages for defective work. Judgment entered. Plaintiff now sues same Defendant for the same contract, seeking additional damages for cost of repairs not included in first complaint.",
    "notes": "**'Same cause of action' = transactional test (modern rule):**\n\n- Claims arise from **same transaction or occurrence** (not same legal theory)\n- **Broader scope** than \"same evidence\" test\n- **Encompassing test:** All claims that could have been raised from one transaction are barred if not raised in first suit\n\n**Application:**\n- Single contract breach = one transaction → all damages claims merged\n- Same accident = one transaction → all tort claims (negligence, strict liability, warranty) merged\n- **Splitting claims** across suits = barred by claim preclusion\n\n**Burden:** Party asserting preclusion must show both claims grow from same transaction/nucleus of operative fact.",
