    "rule": "Effect of Judgment (Elements of Claim Preclusion / Res Judicata & Issue Preclusion)",
    "question": "What are the elements of issue preclusion (collateral estoppel), and how does it differ from claim preclusion in scope?",
    "trigger": "In Case 1, a court determined that Driver was negligent. Driver lost on that issue. In Case 2, a new plaintiff sues Driver for injuries from the same accident. Driver wants to prevent re-litigation of the negligence issue.",
    "notes": "**Issue preclusion (collateral estoppel) elements:**\n\n- **Same issue** of fact or law (not necessarily same cause of action)\n- Issue was **actually litigated** in first action (decided, not assumed)\n- Issue **actually determined** (resolved in judgment)\n- **Final judgment** on the merits\n- **Mutuality** (or non-mutual estoppel applies per modern rule)\n\n**Key Differences from Claim Preclusion:**\n- **Claim preclusion:** Bars entire claim if parties & transaction same\n- **Issue preclusion:** Bars only **specific issues** resolved, even in **different disputes**\n- Narrower in scope but **applies across different claims/parties** (if mutuality satisfied)\n\n**Burden:** Party asserting issue preclusion must prove all five elements; defendant can invoke **non-mutual estoppel** against new plaintiff in modern jurisdictions.",
    "commonVsModern": "",
