    "trigger": "A prosecutor offers gruesome crime scene photos that are probative of the defendant's identity but highly inflammatory. The defendant objects under Rule 403.",
    "notes": "- **Rule 403 standard**: Evidence may be excluded if its probative value is substantially outweighed by a danger of unfair prejudice, confusion, misleading the jury, undue delay, waste of time, or needless presentation of cumulative evidence.\n- **Burden placement**: The party seeking exclusion (typically the opponent) bears the burden of proving that probative value is substantially outweighed by the listed dangers.\n- **'Unfair prejudice'**: Means the evidence will cause the jury to make a decision on an improper basis (emotion, sympathy, anger), not merely that it hurts the opponent.\n- **Timing**: Rule 403 objections must be raised timely; failure to object at trial may waive the objection.",
