    "question": "What categories of 'danger' qualify as grounds for Rule 403 exclusion beyond unfair prejudice?",
    "trigger": "A plaintiff offers 50 pages of technical expert reports, each only slightly relevant to a single issue, to establish a contract term. The defendant moves to exclude under Rule 403.",
    "notes": "- **Listed dangers** (beyond unfair prejudice): **confusion of the issues**, **misleading the jury**, **undue delay**, **waste of time**, **needless presentation of cumulative evidence**.\n- **'Confusion'**: Evidence that obscures the jury's ability to focus on material facts or makes the case harder to follow without corresponding probative value.\n- **'Cumulative evidence'**: Multiple pieces of evidence proving the same point; if later evidence is only marginally more probative, Rule 403 permits exclusion.\n- **'Waste of time'**: Evidence requiring extensive foundational testimony or cross-examination that yields minimal incremental probative value.\n- **Key distinction**: All dangers must still be substantially outweighed by probative value; low probative value tilts the balance toward exclusion.",
