    "trigger": "The judge admits evidence of a defendant's prior business failure as probative of motive to commit fraud, but the connection appears weak. At closing, the prosecutor barely mentions it.",
    "notes": "- **Conditional admission**: Trial judges have discretion to admit evidence conditionally, on the promise that the proponent will establish the necessary foundational link (e.g., relevance to motive).\n- **Conditional relevance (Rule 104(b))**: If the foundation fails to materialize, the evidence's probative value collapses, potentially triggering post-hoc Rule 403 exclusion or jury instructions to disregard.\n- **Curative instruction**: If evidence becomes problematic after admission, the trial judge may limit its use via jury instruction rather than striking it entirely.\n- **No automatic reversal**: Even if evidence was weak, failure to object at trial or move to strike forfeits the right to challenge on appeal unless the error is structural (rare in Rule 403 context).",
