    "question": "Under FRE 701, what lay opinions are explicitly prohibited regardless of the witness's personal perception?",
    "trigger": "A lay witness testifies that 'the defendant's conduct was negligent and violated the standard of care.' Opposing counsel objects to this opinion.",
    "notes": "- **Prohibited lay opinions:** those on **ultimate issues** that involve **legal conclusions** or **standards of law**\n- Witness cannot opine on **negligence, breach of duty, guilt/innocence, liability,** or **legal elements** of a claim or defense\n- **Rationale:** lay opinion on legal conclusions invades the **province of the jury** or court on matters of law\n- Contrast: lay opinion on **factual predicates** underlying legal conclusions is allowed (e.g., 'defendant ran a red light' ✓ vs. 'defendant was negligent' ✗)\n- **Burden on opponent:** object immediately when lay witness crosses into legal conclusion territory",
