    "trigger": "A bystander testifies 'the man I saw at the crime scene was the defendant,' but the defendant argues the lighting was poor and distance was 100 feet. Defense attorney seeks to exclude the identification opinion.",
    "notes": "- **Predicate requirement:** lay witness's **personal perception must be adequate** before opinion is permitted\n- Opponent may challenge via **cross-examination or other evidence** to show perception was unreliable\n- **Witness must have actually perceived** the subject of the opinion (e.g., good viewing opportunity, sufficient familiarity with person identified)\n- **Helpfulness element** also requires opinion assist jury; unreliable perception → not helpful\n- **Burden shifts:** if perception is undermined, opinion becomes inadmissible despite rational basis\n- Judge acts as **gatekeeper** to exclude opinions resting on inadequate factual foundation",
