    "subject": "Evidence - Policy Exclusions",
    "rule": "Spousal Immunity and Confidential Marital Communications Privileges",
    "question": "What is the foundational difference between spousal immunity and the confidential marital communications privilege?",
    "trigger": "A spouse is called to testify about conversations with their partner during marriage. The testifying spouse objects based on spousal protection.",
    "notes": "- **Spousal Immunity**: A **non-testifying spouse** has the right to prevent the other spouse from testifying about **any matter** (communications or observations) during the marriage\n- **Confidential Marital Communications Privilege**: Either spouse may invoke to **exclude statements made in confidence** during marriage, even **after divorce**\n- **Key distinction**: Immunity is about **who can be forced to the stand**; privilege is about **what can be said once there**\n- Immunity is **narrower in scope** but broader in **who holds it**; privilege is **broader in scope** but may be invoked by **either spouse**",
