    "rule": "Statements That Are Not Hearsay: Opposing Party's Statements & Admissions",
    "question": "When is an opposing party's prior statement admissible as a non-hearsay statement rather than requiring it to fit a hearsay exception?",
    "trigger": "Defendant's attorney offers evidence that the defendant told a police officer three months before trial: 'I was at home that night, not at the crime scene.'",
    "notes": "- **Non-hearsay classification**: Opposing party's **own statement** is admissible without a hearsay exception under FRE 801(d)(2)\n- **Key distinction**: Statement need NOT be against defendant's interest at time of trial or at time made\n- **No waiver**: Defendant cannot prevent admission by remaining silent or failing to object pre-trial\n- **Party opponent doctrine**: Any statement by a **party to the litigation** is admissible against that party, regardless of reliability",
