    "subject": "Evidence - Hearsay Foundations",
    "rule": "Right to Confront Witnesses (Sixth Amendment Confrontation Clause & Testimonial Hearsay Bounds)",
    "question": "Does the Confrontation Clause bar admission of testimonial hearsay if the defendant had a prior opportunity to cross-examine the witness?",
    "trigger": "Defendant cross-examined the witness at a preliminary hearing. The witness is now unavailable at trial. Prosecution offers the testimonial statements from the preliminary hearing transcript.",
    "notes": "- **Prior opportunity to cross-examine satisfies Confrontation Clause** — testimonial statements admissible if defendant had adequate prior cross (Crawford, Forfeiture by Wrongdoing doctrine)\n- **Cross must be adequate**: Defendant must have **motive and opportunity to develop same subject matter** at prior proceeding\n- **Unavailability required**: Witness must be unavailable at trial despite **good faith effort** to produce them\n- **Forfeiture exception**: If defendant **wrongfully caused** witness's absence or refusal to testify, Confrontation Clause is forfeited\n- Burden on **prosecution** to prove prior adequate cross or forfeiture",
