    "question": "What factual showing must the proponent make to establish that a statement qualifies as a Present Sense Impression?",
    "trigger": "A witness testifies that the declarant said, 'The light was red when that car ran the intersection,' but there is dispute about when the statement was made relative to the accident.",
    "notes": "- **Required foundation**: Proponent must prove the declarant **perceived the event and narrated it contemporaneously**\n- **Corroboration element**: Statement must be **describing an event actually perceived by the declarant** (not speculation or inference)\n- **Burden shifts to opponent**: Once PSI elements are shown, opponent must challenge **the timing or the declarant's perception**\n- **No requirement for excitement**: Unlike EU, PSI does **not require** the declarant to be emotionally aroused\n- **Bar exam pin**: Declarant availability is irrelevant—both exceptions apply whether declarant testifies or not",
