    "subject": "Real Property - Cotenancies",
    "rule": "Joint Tenancy (Four Unities), Tenancy in Common, and Tenancy by the Entirety",
    "question": "What is the default presumption for cotenancies in common law jurisdictions, and how is it rebutted?",
    "trigger": "A and B take title to land under a single deed that is silent as to the type of cotenancy. No marriage; no survivorship language. Each claims different rights.",
    "notes": "**Default Presumption – Tenancy in Common:**\n- **Modern common law rule:** ambiguous/silent conveyances create **TIC**, NOT JT\n- Reflects preference against survivorship and unilateral inalienability\n- JT must be **explicitly stated** in the deed ('joint tenancy,' 'right of survivorship')\n\n**Exceptions to TIC Default:**\n- **Spouses:** Many jurisdictions presume tenancy by entirety unless otherwise stated\n- **Rebuttal:** Clear language ('tenants in common,' 'each owns separate share') overcomes presumption\n- Here: Ambiguous deed + no marriage + no survivorship language = **TIC** (not JT)",
