    "subject": "Real Property - Cotenancies",
    "rule": "Partition Remedies and Procedural Methods",
    "question": "What factors determine whether a court orders in-kind partition versus partition by sale?",
    "trigger": "Two cotenants in rural farmland seek partition. One wants physical division into two separate parcels; the other argues the land cannot be fairly divided without destroying its value.",
    "notes": "- **Default preference**: **In-kind partition** (physical division) preferred if **land is capable of division without substantial loss of value**\n- **Triggering partition by sale**: Court orders sale if: (1) **land cannot be fairly divided** (e.g., small/unique property), (2) **in-kind partition would cause substantial injury** to property value, or (3) **cotenants cannot agree on division terms**\n- **Burden shift**: Proponent of sale bears burden showing in-kind partition **impracticable**\n- **Modern trend**: Increasingly favoring sale over physical division for practical/economic reasons",
