    "question": "What is the test for an EASEMENT IMPLIED FROM PRIOR USE, and what burden of proof applies?",
    "trigger": "O owns two adjacent parcels. Before selling parcel B, O had used a path on parcel A to access parcel B. The deed to B contains no mention of this path. B's owner now claims an easement to continue using the path.",
    "notes": "**Four Elements (Strict Test):**\n- **Easement existed during common ownership** of both parcels\n- **Easement was apparent and continuous** (not occasional or latent)\n- **Easement was reasonably necessary** for the enjoyment of the dominant land (not merely convenient)\n- **Parties intended easement to continue** after severance (inferred from prior use pattern)\n\n**Burden of Proof:**\n- Claimant bears **clear and convincing evidence** standard\n- Courts construe **narrowly** against easement; easement limited to scope of prior use\n- **No easement by prior use** if grantor never actually used the path pre-sale",
