    "rule": "Marketability of Title Standards (Chain Defects, Encumbrances, Timing, Merger Defenses)",
    "question": "What types of title defects render title unmarketable under the majority rule?",
    "trigger": "A seller's title search reveals a 30-year-old judgment lien against the property and an easement granted to a neighbor in 1995. The buyer refuses to close, claiming title is unmarketable.",
    "notes": "- **Unmarketable defects** = defects that reasonably prudent buyer would refuse to accept\n- **Chain of title gaps** (breaks in recorded ownership sequence) render title unmarketable\n- **Encumbrances** (liens, easements, covenants, mortgages) render title unmarketable **unless** disclosed in contract or waived by buyer\n- **Judgment liens** = marketability defect (affects buyer's quiet enjoyment & resale)\n- **Easements** = marketability defect (burden runs with land)\n- **Note**: Minor, ancient easements may be insurable; depends on jurisdiction's treatment of marketability vs. insurability",
