    "rule": "Marketability of Title Standards (Chain Defects, Encumbrances, Timing, Merger Defenses)",
    "question": "What is the relationship between marketability of title and title insurance in resolving seller-buyer disputes?",
    "trigger": "Seller tenders title policy insuring against all defects except a 1982 easement. Buyer demands easement removal as condition of closing. Seller argues title insurance satisfies the marketability requirement.",
    "notes": "- **Marketable title** ≠ **insurable title** (distinct standards)\n- **Marketable title rule**: Seller must deliver title **free of defects** (easement must be removed/released)\n- **Title insurance rule**: Seller may satisfy duty by providing **comprehensive policy** covering known encumbrances **OR** insuring over them\n- **Exceptions clause**: Defects listed in Schedule B (exceptions) = **title insurance does NOT protect buyer**\n- **Majority rule**: Title insurance alone does **NOT cure unmarketability** unless contract permits 'title insurance quality' standard\n- **Minority/modern approach**: If contract silent, **insurable title satisfies** marketability obligation (burden shifts to buyer to accept policy exceptions)\n- **Practical outcome**: Review contract language; if 'marketable title' specified, seller must cure; if 'insurable' acceptable, exceptions permitted",
