    "subject": "Professional Responsibility - Confidentiality of Information",
    "rule": "MRPC Rule 1.6(a), (c): General duty not to reveal information relating to representation without informed consent or applicable exception, and duty to make reasonable efforts to prevent inadvertent or unauthorized disclosure.",
    "question": "Under MRPC 1.6(a), what is the foundational scope of information a lawyer must keep confidential?",
    "trigger": "A lawyer learns during client intake that the client is planning to commit tax fraud. The client has not yet asked the lawyer to help with the scheme.",
    "notes": "- **Scope**: Applies to **all information relating to the representation**, not just privileged communications\n- Includes both **privileged** and **non-privileged** information\n- Covers information obtained from **client, third parties, or opposing counsel** during representation\n- No requirement that information be explicitly marked confidential or that client request secrecy\n- **Core duty**: Protect **any fact about the representation** absent consent or exception",
