    "subject": "Professional Responsibility - Confidentiality of Information",
    "rule": "MRPC Rule 1.6(a), (c): General duty not to reveal information relating to representation without informed consent or applicable exception, and duty to make reasonable efforts to prevent inadvertent or unauthorized disclosure.",
    "question": "What must a lawyer obtain from a client to disclose confidential information, and what does that consent require?",
    "trigger": "A client tells a lawyer: 'You can tell my accountant about this deal.' The lawyer wants to provide a detailed report to the CPA.",
    "notes": "- **Consent standard**: Must be **informed consent** under MRPC 1.0(e)\n- **Informed consent requires**: Client understands **nature, risks, and reasonably foreseeable consequences** of disclosure\n- **Specificity matters**: General consent (e.g., 'use your judgment') may not satisfy **informed consent** requirement\n- **Burden on lawyer**: Must ensure client **actually understands** what will be disclosed and to whom\n- **Scope limitation**: Consent to disclose to accountant does **not** authorize disclosure to third parties absent additional consent",
