    "subject": "Professional Responsibility - Confidentiality of Information",
    "rule": "MRPC Rule 1.6(a), (c): General duty not to reveal information relating to representation without informed consent or applicable exception, and duty to make reasonable efforts to prevent inadvertent or unauthorized disclosure.",
    "question": "Under MRPC 1.6, when does confidentiality duty terminate, and what information remains protected?",
    "trigger": "A lawyer represented a client five years ago on a real estate matter. The representation ended when the deal closed. The lawyer is now approached by opposing counsel in an unrelated litigation for information from that old file.",
    "notes": "- **Duty survives**: Confidentiality continues **after representation ends**—no automatic termination date\n- **No exception for 'inactive' clients** or passage of time alone\n- **Applies to**: Information from **any prior or current representation** without express exception\n- **Rare termination**: Only when information becomes **public through non-lawyer sources** or **applicable exception** arises (e.g., crime-fraud exception under 1.6(b))\n- **Burden remains on lawyer**: Must treat old client files with **same confidentiality duty** as active matters",
