    "trigger": "A lawyer simultaneously represents both a landlord and tenant, but in separate, unrelated disputes with third parties—neither client is adverse to the other.",
    "notes": "**Direct adversity (non-waivable inherently problematic):**\n- Lawyer's representation of Client A is **actively adverse to Client B in the same or substantially related matter**\n- Example: Same real estate transaction, litigation on opposite sides, contract negotiation between them\n- **Cannot be waived by informed consent alone** if truly adverse in same matter\n\n**Material limitation risk (potentially waivable):**\n- Clients are not directly opposed but **significant risk** loyalty/confidentiality/independent judgment compromised\n- Example: Related matters where strategies might diverge, or duty to one client limits duty to another\n- **May be waivable** with informed written consent if lawyer reasonably believes representation competent and undivided\n- **Burden shifts to lawyer to prove waivability** once conflict identified",
