    "subject": "Professional Responsibility - Meritorious Claims and Contentions",
    "rule": "MRPC Rule 3.1: Requirement that claims and contentions have a basis in law and fact and are not frivolous, including good-faith arguments for extension, modification, or reversal of existing law.",
    "question": "Under MRPC 3.1, what is the foundational requirement a lawyer must satisfy before filing a claim or contention in court?",
    "trigger": "A lawyer wants to file a complaint asserting that the defendant breached a contract, but has minimal factual support and no case law directly on point.",
    "notes": "- **Core requirement**: A claim or contention must have a basis in **both law AND fact**\n- Lawyer bears burden of reasonable inquiry before filing\n- **Frivolous claims violate 3.1** (those with no reasonable basis in law or fact)\n- Applies to **all claims, defenses, and contentions** in pleadings and motions\n- Does NOT require certainty of success—only a non-frivolous basis",
