    "question": "Does MRPC 3.1 permit a lawyer to assert a position that extends, modifies, or reverses existing law? If so, under what condition?",
    "trigger": "A lawyer wants to argue in a brief that prior precedent interpreting a statute should be overruled based on a novel constitutional theory.",
    "notes": "- **YES**: Good-faith arguments for **extension, modification, or reversal** of existing law are permitted\n- **Condition**: The argument must be made in **good faith**—not as a pretense or delaying tactic\n- Distinguishes between **frivolous reversal arguments** (barred) and **good-faith novel arguments** (permitted)\n- Purpose: Protects lawyer's ability to advocate for legal change without violating 3.1\n- Burden on lawyer: Must demonstrate good-faith basis, not mere hope or speculation",
