    "subject": "Professional Responsibility - Candor Toward the Tribunal",
    "rule": "MRPC Rule 3.3(a)(1)-(2): Prohibitions on knowingly making false statements of fact or law to a tribunal or failing to correct such statements, and on failing to disclose controlling adverse legal authority not disclosed by opposing counsel.",
    "question": "Does MRPC 3.3(a)(2)'s duty to disclose controlling adverse authority apply when the lawyer discovers the authority after opposing counsel has already cited it?",
    "trigger": "During rebuttal, opposing counsel cites a controlling adverse case. The lawyer discovers a more recent controlling case that distinguishes or limits the cited case.",
    "notes": "- **Duty still applies**: Lawyer must consider whether the **new adverse authority** is also controlling\n- **\"Not disclosed by opposing counsel\" test**: The rule only excuses disclosure when opposing counsel **already cited** the authority\n- **Multiple adverse authorities**: If lawyer knows of **multiple controlling adverse sources**, each must be evaluated\n- **Strategic disclosure caveat**: Lawyer may argue application or distinguishability, but **cannot remain silent** on controlling authority",
